title: Football By The Numbers for Week Six
text:
Football By The Numbers for Week Six Dena Bowl Chesapeake at Northeast FBB By Matthew Cole / Capital Gazette 
Lightning dances across the sky behind Northeast High School's football stadium during the annual "Dena Bowl" at Northeast High School in Pasadena, Friday night. Many area games were affected by the weather over the weekend. Chesapeake wound up winning the Dena Bowl for the fifth year in a row, on Monday, Oct. 12. 
Lightning dances across the sky behind Northeast High School's football stadium during the annual "Dena Bowl" at Northeast High School in Pasadena, Friday night. Many area games were affected by the weather over the weekend. Chesapeake wound up winning the Dena Bowl for the fifth year in a row, on Monday, Oct. 12. (By Matthew Cole / Capital Gazette) Katherine Dunn Contact Reporter Which three All-Metro players had 2 interceptions each this week? 
Rain washed away some Friday high school football games for the second weekend in a row and delayed By The Numbers again, but three days of football games provided plenty of stellar stats for another week. This edition features two interceptions each by three All-Metro players, lengthy league winning streaks by three teams and a quarterback who has thrown for a season's worth of yardage in just seven games. 
Here are the stats that stood out over this long weekend: 
1 
Blocked extra point attempt by Havre de Grace’s Judeah Sale in a 21-19 win over North Harford. 
2 
Interceptions by Franklin’s Steven Smothers in a 40-0 win over Milford Mill 
2 (Katherine Dunn) 
2 
Interceptions by Broadneck’s Ali’i Niumatalolo, including one in overtime, of the Bruins’ 49-42 win over Arundel 
5 
Straight wins for Chesapeake-AA over Northeast in the Dena Bowl with Monday’s 41-6 victory 
5 
Touchdown passes thrown by Old Mill quarterback David Marrocco in the first half of a 67-6 win over North County 
6 
Touchdowns scored by Archbishop Spalding quarterback Evan Fochtman – four passing, two rushing – in a 42-7 win over Calvert Hall 
6 
Undefeated teams left in the Baltimore area – Old Mill, Howard, John Carroll, Eastern Tech, Dundalk and Mervo 
7 
Straight wins by John Carroll, the area’s longest active win streak 
11.7 
Yard average gain by South Carroll, which rushed for 375 yards, in a 41-0 win over Winters Mill 
15 
Minute delay for the stadium lights going out on top of a 90-minute storm delay in Reservoir’s 26-7 win over Glenelg 
18 
Straight regular-season wins by Mervo, including 17 straight against Baltimore City opponents 
20 
Straight wins by Howard over Howard County opponents. 
22 
Straight wins by Franklin over Baltimore County opponents 
28 
Straight points scored by Marriotts Ridge in a 28-15 win over Oakland Mills 
38 
Carries by four Reservoir players – Josh Young, Daniel Huling, Barry Carter and Ebissa Sambo – for 363 yards and three touchdowns in the win over Glenelg 
55 
Yard field goal kicked by Boy’s Latin’s Dom Maggio in 41-22 win over John Carroll -- four yards shy of the state record 
73 
Hours for John Carroll and Boys' Latin to complete their game after thunderstorms postponed it from Friday afternoon until Monday 
85 
Yard touchdown run by Jamar Williams on South Carroll’s first play from scrimmage in the win over Winters Mill 
100 
Career wins by Franklin’s Anthony Burgos with the win over Milford Mill 
130 
Yards receiving for Calvert Hall’s Morgan Scroggins in the loss to Archbishop Spalding 
208 
Yards passing by Archbishop Curley quarterback Luke Nakich on six completions in a 35-13 win over Severn 
510 
Yards gained on the ground as Glen Burnie’s Greg Avent, Dami Adekunjo and Taylor Johnson ran for more than 100 yards each in a 36-2 win over Southern-AA 
2,042 
Yards passing in seven games by John Carroll’s Kurt Rasmussen, who threw for 267 yards and scored six touchdowns in the win over Boys’ Latin 
( Note : By The Numbers will be taking a week off and will resume Oct. 25th or 26th -- or 27th if it rains again.)
